shared_text:
Diane Hedahl is with Gracie Claridge.
May 23 at 7:24 PM ·

Class of 2020… we blinked and you started Kindergarten, we blinked again and you are graduating High School. We sought to give you roots and wings. Our hope is, that both are strong enough to help you realize your dreams and help you make a difference in this world. The world truly is your oyster, but only with a bit of grit, will you end up with that pearl. You will make mistakes, but they do not define who you are, unless you let them. They are just experiences to learn from. Life doesn't come with a road map, don't be afraid to ask for guidance. Remember the past and learn from it. Live in the present and be present for those you're with. Electronic gadgetry will never fill the void that was meant for human connections. Look to the future, it's one big adventure that someday you'll look back on. How you live it, day by day, will determine whether you look back with smiles and laughter, or with regret. This really is the beginning of the rest of your life. Wishing you all the very best!!

post_text:
Today, is National Teacher Appreciation Day. We definitely appreciate ours!! It has been said that a teacher is like a candle, it consumes itself to light the way for others. Our teachers have always been dedicated professionals, often putting in long hours while going above and beyond. In recent weeks, they have been challenged to learn more, plan more and give more. And like the true heroes they are, they have risen to the challenge. Thompson Falls Schools are fortunate to have some of the very finest teachers!! We salute you and thank you for all that you do!!

Special thanks to our AWESOME PTO for showering a little love on our staff this week in the form of some beautiful blooming plants!!

Thank You Samie Helvey, Patti Lyght, Connie Gunderson, Sherri Koskela, Pam Brophy and Lindy Cooper!! You are heroes indeed!!!

Notarized declarations may also be dropped off at the county election office located in the Sanders County Courthouse.

Close of filing is March 26th at 5:00pm. Close of Write-In Declaration filing is April 2nd at 5:00pm.

post_text:
Hattie Neesvig, an 8th grader at Thompson Falls Junior High School, will be conducting her 5th annual book drive. She is asking for preschool-aged books that are brand new or gently used. The books will be distributed across Sanders County (in handcrafted book bags created by Hattie) to children in need during the holiday season. Hattie believes this gives children a good start to their education, making them more successful in the future. A single book can change a child's life, so please join Hattie in helping our community.
Donated books may be left in the Book Box, located in the Elementary Hallway. The drive will run December 2nd through December 6th. Hattie thanks you for your help and support! We thank Hattie for making a difference!

post_text: Our Junior High Students participated in our Annual Leaf Raking event this past week. The Junior High has been reaching out to our community members that are in need of some help raking leaves for a few years, and it has been great! Thank you all who welcomed our kids to their lawns this year! We have a couple more that, if weather permitting and classes allow, we will be visiting. Here are some pictures of our amazing kids giving back to a supportive community.

post_text:
Our BOOSTER CLUB is looking for new members and supporters! This is a great way to support our BlueHawks! The goal of the BOOSTER CLUB is to raise funds for scholarships and to support extra-curricular activities. They aim to promote team and school enthusiasm, pride in our sportsmanship and community involvement.

Their next meeting is scheduled for Thursday, November 14th @ 6:00PM in the High School Library.

Don't have time for another meeting in your schedule? The BOOSTER CLUB is also looking for sponsors!! The sponsor form can be found here: https://www.thompsonfalls.net/cms/lib/MT15000216/Centricity/Domain/63/Sponsorletter%202.pdf

Thank you for your ongoing support of our students!
